data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — gives you `"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"` on failure instead of just `"Expected: True, Actual: False"`
- **`CollectionAssert`** — MSTest's built-in collection helper. Also offers `Contains`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `IsSubsetOf`, `AreEquivalent` (same items, any order), etc.
- **Message parameters** — the string arg on `Assert.IsTrue` tells you *what* failed
- **`Any()` over `Single()`** — avoids an exception when the test should just fail cleanly

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
// Exact sequence match (order matters)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Type checking
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Membership
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, specificUser);
```

**Rule of thumb:** avoid `Assert.IsTrue(someBool)` when a more specific assertion exists — you lose all diagnostic info on failure.
